Developing Data Products Week 2 Assessment Jack Quarm 23/04/2020

What’s up with that COVID-19 Business?


Yeah, yeah, I know another COVID-19 map…

The leaflet package makes it easy to represent geographical data in R. Using the addCircles() argument, we’ll attempt to view the 10 countries world-wide with the highest number of confirmed cases of COVID-19 by setting the radius of the circle proportional to the number of confirmed cases.

We’re also going to colour-code the map with a completely arbitrary display of ‘severity’ with:

  • Red: displaying countries with more than 200,000 cases.
  • Orange: displaying countries with more than 150,000 cases.
  • Green: displaying countries with less than 100,000 cases.

For the purposes of this assessment, i’ll hardcode the dataset in, so you can see how the leaflet package works. Bear in mind it’ll obviously be out of date by the time you’ve published it. If you’re looking for a great live-tracking app, check out the COVID-19 Dashboard by the Center for Systems Science and Engineering (CSSE) at Johns Hopkins University (JHU).


COVID-19 Dashboard by the Center for Systems Science and Engineering (CSSE) at Johns Hopkins University (JHU)


Covid-19 Map as of 23/04/2020

# Load the package
library(leaflet)

# Create data set to display with the map
cities <- data.frame(
  names = c("US", "Spain", "Italy", "France", "Germany", "UK", "Turkey", "Iran", "China", "Russia"),
  cases = c(847985, 213024, 189973, 157135, 151195, 139245, 101790, 87026, 83878, 62773),
  lat = c(39.8283, 40.5531, 41.8719, 46.2276, 51.1657, 55.3781, 38.9637, 32.4279, 35.8617, 61.5240),
  lng = c(-98.5795, -3.4699, 12.5674, 2.2137, 10.4515, 3.4360, 35.2433, 53.6880, 104.1959, 105.3188))

# Add some comments to make it easier to read
comments <- c("US: 847,985 Cases", "Spain: 213,024 Cases", "Italy: 189,973 Cases", "France: 157,135 Cases", "Germany: 151,195 Cases", "UK: 139,245 Cases", "Turkey: 101,790 Cases", "Iran: 87,026 Cases", "China: 83,878 Cases", "Russia: 62,773 Cases")

# Make the map
map <- cities %>%
  leaflet() %>%
  addTiles() %>%
  addCircles(weight = 1, radius = (cities$cases*5), popup = comments, color = c("red", "red", "red", "orange", "orange", "orange", "orange", "green", "green", "green")) %>%
  addLegend(labels = c("US", "Spain", "Italy", "France", "Germany", "UK", "Turkey", "Iran", "China", "Russia"), colors = c("red", "red", "red", "orange", "orange", "orange", "orange", "green", "green", "green"))


There you have it, a fully interactive map
